"I'm home... Wait?"

When I returned, I was greeted by an empty hut.

The situation was the same as when I left, and Konomi seemed to have left the house shortly after I did.

"...Ah, I see. Maybe Konomi went back to the elf village while I was away..."

Konomi may never come back.

I felt the anxiety I had felt last night make the hairs on my back stand on end.

It's not that I don't believe in Konomi.

But not having him by my side makes me feel so anxious.

Such is the fickleness of elves. If it is easy to choose me, it will be just as easy to abandon me.

There is practically no reason for her to choose me.

If there was something there that interested Konomi more than me, it wouldn't be strange at all if she went there.

"...Instead of thinking about such pointless things, let's make some sweets. Even if Konomi doesn't come back, we can have some as a preserved food."

There's no need to become more self-deprecating than necessary just because you're feeling anxious.

I'm already prepared to lose Konomi.

Konomi will be returned to the elf village by the full moon. I haven't told her this yet, but it's clear in my mind.

After all, if I die, Konomi will probably disappear before too long.

I don't have any plans to die anytime soon, but to an elf, a human's life is but the blink of an eye.

Considering what will happen to Konomi after I die, it's definitely best to send her back to the elf village now.

Therefore, Konomi will return to the elf village before the full moon when the barrier closes.

Apparently in the elf village they burn tokiwasure flowers near the barrier, so Konomi will probably forget about me eventually.

Even if you're sad because we broke up, the sadness won't last forever.

Besides, if we spend too much time together, I'll grow old and die first. If I can send Konomi back inside the barrier, she'll be able to escape that sadness.

I once again looked around the cabin where I had stayed with Konomi.

Maybe there was some reason why he hadn't returned before I did.

I shook my head to clear my sentimental feelings and put my luggage down.

Konomi would probably get in the way if she was here anyway, so I decided to bake some sweets for her before she returned so the two of us could eat them together.

Plus, I'm sure Konomi would be happy if some sweets were unexpectedly prepared for her.

Although not as much as Hinata or Ibara, Konomi didn't seem to dislike sweets either.

Without thinking about anything else, just thinking about Konomi's happy face, let's bake sweets. Let's bake lots of sweets.

Baking sweets is difficult because of the ingredients and the heat. If you focus on the task at hand, you won't be overwhelmed by unfounded anxiety.

You don't have to dwell on the sadness of breaking up.

I tore off a piece of the tasteless bread I'd bought in the village and popped it into my mouth, then measured out some flour before I even had a meal.

